‚Ä¢
According to contemporaryobgyn.net, ‚ÄúCompared to white women, black women were significantly less likely to be diagnosed with endometriosis (OR 0.49; 95% CI: 0.29 ‚Äì 083). The same held true for Hispanic women (OR 0.46; 95% CI: 0.14 ‚Äì 1.50).‚Äù
‚Ä¢
My sister has stage IV Endometriosis, a very complicated disease that has had her undergo several surgeries through the years and more to come to treat the incurable disease. She has suffered since childhood, but wasn‚Äôt diagnosed until it had ravaged most of her body as a young adult. She was diagnosed & treated by both Black and Indian physicians.
‚Ä¢
I have suffered similarity, but not nearly to the extent she has, haven‚Äôt had any surgeries, and have still not been diagnosed. Surgery is typically the way to diagnose & I am not a candidate for it.
‚Ä¢
Ladies, it is important to not accept the passiveness and temporary treatment that only subdues the symptoms, often given to Blacks and women of color, when it comes to your health. Don‚Äôt suffer in silence. Please consult Black physicians and get your healing. üíõüíõüíõüíõ
‚Ä¢
